  "stage": {
    "id": "course_1_foundations",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Foundations of Large Language Models",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "large_language_models",
        "title": "What Are Large Language Models?",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Neural networks trained on massive text\n- Predict next tokens\n- Foundation of modern AI\n\nTouvron et al. (2023) introduced Llama 2, a family of large language models trained on 2 trillion tokens. An LLM is like a super-powered text prediction machine—given some text, it predicts what word should come next. This simple idea, scaled to billions of parameters and trillions of tokens, creates surprisingly intelligent behavior.\n\nThink of it like learning to write by reading millions of books. You pick up patterns: after 'Once upon a time', a story usually follows. After 'The capital of France is', you expect 'Paris'. LLMs learn these patterns at massive scale.",
        "position": {
          "x": 3,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "transformer_architecture",
        "title": "The Transformer: Attention Over Recurrence",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Self-attention mechanism\n- Parallel computation\n- Position encoding\n\nTransformers replaced older recurrent architectures by using 'attention'—a mechanism where each word token can look at relevant previous tokens to understand context. Imagine reading a sentence: when you see 'it', you look back to find what 'it' refers to. Transformers do this automatically for all tokens in parallel, making training much faster.\n\nLlama 2 is built entirely on Transformers. The key innovation is self-attention: each position in the text learns what to pay attention to.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "autoregressive_language_modeling",
        "title": "Autoregressive Training: Predicting One Token at a Time",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Causal masking\n- Next-token prediction\n- Sequential generation\n\nAutoregressive means 'self-generating': the model predicts the next token given everything that came before. During training, if the text is 'The cat sat on the', the model learns to predict 'mat' as the next word.\n\nThis is implemented using causal masking in the Transformer—tokens can only look at previous tokens, not future ones. During generation, the model keeps adding one token at a time, each informed by all previous tokens. Simple but powerful!",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "pretraining",
        "title": "Pretraining on 2 Trillion Tokens",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Public data sources\n- Massive scale\n- Broad knowledge acquisition\n\nLlama 2 underwent massive pretraining on 2 trillion tokens—text from the internet, books, code repositories, and more. This is like reading billions of pages of diverse content. The model learns not just grammar but world knowledge, coding patterns, math, reasoning, and much more.\n\nPretraining is the most expensive phase but creates a foundation of general knowledge. All subsequent fine-tuning builds on this pretrained base.",
        "position": {
          "x": 15,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "Llama 2 was pretrained on approximately: 1) 100 billion tokens, 2) 500 billion tokens, 3) 2 trillion tokens. Which?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "True",
        "False"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "2 trillion tokens",
